snippet.textDisplay:
A beautiful piece of fine art. I'm an ancinet proponent of mixing Indian classical with western music. Thanks CS for doing this for a few years now.

But I like to differ on one point. To me it is a fusion of Raags Sindhi Bharvi and Asaavri. At around 013 it seems to begins as Sindhi Bhaviri. At 3.57 it shifts to Asaavri. Sindhi Bharvi is a branch of Asaavri Thhaat. 

I like a music scholar to please enlighten me on my this observation and comments.
snippet.textOriginal:
A beautiful piece of fine art. I'm an ancinet proponent of mixing Indian classical with western music. Thanks CS for doing this for a few years now.

I like a music scholar to please enlighten me on my this observation and comments.
